\begin_layout Standard
We believe that such a comparison of consumption and education expenses
 against prosperity and consumer characteristics such as education, asset-level
 and occupation may have implications for two specific areas of research.
 First, the consumer characteristics and prosperity may have implications
 for migration pressures in the economy.
 More particularly, if the costs of living and amenities are less varied
 across reference areas in the economy, then a consumer may be indifferent
 between staying in a poorer reference and a moving to a higher reference
 with higher relative poverty.
 This - however - changes when the difference in reference areas are extreme
 in terms of opportunities and prevent immediate mobility (to surrounding
 areas).
 Second, the distribution of educational and occupational skills across
 the economy influences the access to certain types of consumption - which
 may have implications for status-related consumption in the economy.
 When a poorer reference has less opportunities both for mobility and status
 consumption, then the escape to a richer reference may act as a door to
 improbable mobilities for the consumer - amounting to a change of context
 more important to the consumer than a simple gain in income levels.
\end_layout

