 In particular, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "roperclassifyingresp1940"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 notes the inadequacies of an objective notion of status - suggesting that
 the context of the consumer be measured and accounted for in order to have
 a better understanding of status.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea of reference group - which summarises the role of the consumer's
 environment in her decision making - was expanded upon by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HymanStatuPsych1942"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 who also addressed how a certain subjective notion of status that the consumer
 responds to - may differ from the objective notion of status.
 While considering reference groups in the context of status, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HymanStatuPsych1942"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 enumerates three types of statuses - the objective, the subjective and
 accorded status.
 These notions of status have considered of importance in the later the
 seminal work from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RuncimanRelativeDeprivationSocialJustice1966"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 as well.
 Focusing on relative deprivation in Britain, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RuncimanRelativeDeprivationSocialJustice1966"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 notes three types of reference groups that could be relevant in a study
 - the reference group could be a comparative group (one the consumer compares
 herself to), a membership group (which the consumer thinks she belongs
 to) or a normative group (where the consumer gets her standards from).
 Depending on a given perspective, the criteria for identifying a reference
 group may vary - but the notion of reference groups remains of key importance
 in much of literature in social sciences - including the current behavioural
 approaches to decision under risk (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MarkowitzUtil1952,KahnemanTversykPT1979"
literal "false"

\end_inset

